# Distributed locks

- Use locks only when necessary — prefer idempotent operations and unique constraints in DB.
- Redis Redlock or etcd/consul locks for short-lived coordination (< 30s hold time).
- Always set lock TTL; crashes must not hold locks forever.
- Include lock owner identity in the lock value; verify ownership before release.
- Keep critical sections inside locks minimal — no network I/O or LLM calls while holding.
- Implement lock renewal (heartbeat) for longer operations if unavoidable.
- Handle lock acquisition failure gracefully (retry with jitter, fallback path).
- Never use distributed locks for throughput scaling — they serialize work.
- Test failure scenarios: lock holder crash, network partition, clock drift.
- Prefer database advisory locks or optimistic locking for data consistency when possible.
